review_blob: A very drinkable, solid imp stout. ABV is well hidden. Taste is of dark chocolate, coffee, with a little sweetness of raisins thrown in. Plesantly surprised by this one. Will age a couple of bombers to see how the flavors change.
beer_name: Left Hand Wake Up Dead Imperial Stout

review_blob: Appearance is was what one would expect from an imp stout - pitch black. Very little head, though, and low carbonation. Big tastes of chocolate, raisin, and molasses. ABV is well hidden by taste, but its defintely felt. Finish was a little sweet for my taste - more reminiscent of a barley wine than an imp stout. Overall a great beer, though not the best imp stout Ive ever had.

Disappointing. Appearance and aroma were what you expect from a craft IPA, but taste was a downer. There was a definite hop presence but thats about it. No piney or citrusy notes here Blah is the best I can say.

Nitro on tap @ Blue 5 in Roanoke, VA.  This is a totall different beer on nitro vs. the bottle.  Mouthfeel is that of a Gunniess, and the double+ abv (vs. Gunniess) is well hidden, which makes for a dangerous combo as one can quaf two or three of these quite easily in a pretty short time span.  Try doing that with OR in the bottle.  Its a totally different experience.  The nitro masks muchof the dark chocolaty bitterness and  (again) alcohol found in the bottle.  I beleive RBDC should have separate ratings for OR bottle and nitro.  Theyre two totally different beers.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: I was pleasantly surprised by this one.  Expecting a ho-hum, mass-produced IPA, I gotta lotta piney, citrusy, hop aroma right off the bat.  Appearance was spot on:  light copper color, good, thick head.  Taste was much better than I had anticipated.  Hop assertiveness was there, alcohol heft was decent (though a kick up to 7 or 7.5% would make this an even more mouth watering beer).  Again, I was surprised and would definitely recommend if youre a hophead.

A good soild DIPA.  Hop taste is dialed back and alcohol presence is well hidden.  Very drinkable.  Much smoother mouthfeel and taste than I expected.  I could "session" drink these, but at 9.1 abv I would definitly feel it the next day.
beer_name: Great Lakes Lake Erie Monster Imperial IPA

review_blob: A little too sweet for my taste, but have to give props where props are due.  Tremendous coffee and semi-sweet chocolate aroma.  Mouthfeel is velvety smooth.  10% abv is well hidden.  A top notch brew.

On tap @ brew pub.  Nice dark golden appearance.  Some fruitiness in the initial taste, but then you taste the reason why they call this a "sour".  Alcohol is nicely hidden, though.  Not one of my favorite styles, but a good sipping beer to spend a half hour or so reading or in quite thought.

12 oz bottle.  One of the better (if not best) of SAs multitude of offerings.  I always do the light test when I pour a stout: if no light penetrates through the glass, its a good stout in my book.  And this one is about as dark and thick as it gets.  The licorice notes are prevalent throughout, as is the alcohol presence. I generally tilt towards the coffee/chocolate-like stouts, but the licoricey(?) mouthfeel of this one is not one youll find in many imp stouts.  Defintley worth the $9-10/four-pack.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Imperial Series Imperial Stout

review_blob: 22 oz bomber.  Thick, thick head.  Pumpkinish tint.  Mouthfeel a little on the syrupy side, yet hop presence is defintely there.  And so is alcohol.  Not my favorite style but still a good solid beverage.

I was pleasantly surprised by this beer.  Tremendous floral floral, piney aroma as soon as I popped the cap.  When poured, light hazy, bronze color was also inviting, as was the solid fluffy head.  A subtle palate hid the stiff resin-like, DIPA bitterness hopheads so crave.  A solid DIPA that I would recommend and buy again.

A bit too flowery for my taste/nose.  Indeed, aroma was overpoweringly floral at the beginning.  Definitive hop bite was there, as was the bitter aftertaste.  Not a bad IPA, though certainly not a great one.  One interesting thing I noticed as the beer warmed (I was soloing a bomber) and I swilled the final gulp, I noticed an acrid, yet familiar scent whafting from the bottom of my imperial pint glass.  I swear I whiffed the subtle, yet all-too-familiar, and (dare I say) even slightly tantilizing scent of dried.... naw, couldnt be!

Bomber.  This one has all the asthetics of a classic IS: motor-oil black color, pervasive choco-coffee aroma, and a nice kick-in-the-pants alcohol wang.  I wouldve liked a bit more roasty flavor a la Old Rasputin, but overall this brew is a solid example of the style.
beer_name: Laughing Dog The Dogfather Imperial Stout

review_blob: A well-balanced DIPA.  Not as hoopy as I wouldve liked &#
beer_name: Laughing Dog Alpha Dog Imperial IPA

review_blob: An outstanding example of whiskey-barrel-aged imperial stout.  Nice creamy head w/ massive coffee, whiskey aromas.  Body is heavy and alcohol presence is pervasive.  Taste is of strong coffee w/ a shot or two of whiskey thrown in.  This beer is not for the faint of heart, but if you enjoy a great, warm-you-to-your-bones stout on a cold winters day, this one will get your motor runnin.
beer_name: Moon River Oak-Aged Black River Imperial Stout

review_blob: Very disappotined in this beer seeing that it comes from Rogue.  Yes, its a malt liquor, but still I expected more from Rogue.  Almost tasteless from the onset.  Nice alcohol feel is about the only positive I can muster.  If I want to drink a tasteless, high-alcohol beer Ill drink an Ice House or something.
beer_name: Rogue Dads Little Helper Malt Liquor

review_blob: Very woody flavor, especially the aftertaste.  Nice color, good head.  I agree w/ one of the earlier reviewers who described it as an "odd beer".  I agree, but thats a good thing.  Never quite had a beer like this one.  I would get this beer again, despite its heafty $8 price tag for a 24 oz bottle.

11.2 oz bottle from Greens on Ponce.  I was more than pleasantly surprised by this one.  A tremendous coffee aroma, tar-black color, and, of course, a BIG coffee/expresso flavor.  Alcohol is very well hidden and palate is incredibly smooth for a big stout like this.  Man, I could have one of these at breakfast every morning!  Its that good.  Highly recommend it.

I was very dissapointed in this beer.  I expected much more.  Too doughy and no metallic bite like from classic Euro pils like Urquell, Staro Prama, St Pauli Girl, etc.  This beer was way too expensive to be as below average as it was.  Dont waste your money on this one.

Normally not a big fan of "fruity" beers, but this one isnt bad.  Slight apricot twang is more than compensated by the familiar, yummy bite of hops.  Might make a good "intro" IPA for women not accustomed to the normally masculine IPA style.  I know - ally non-PC, but thats the fact.

"Natty", like all bargain beers, has its place, like when playing a round of golf on a typically scorching mid GA summer day.  Having a nice iced-down twelver of Natty in the golf cart sure beats drinking water.  Indeed, why waste $7 on a sixer of tasty heifeweizen when you could buy a twelver of Natty for that same price?  When its a 100 degrees youre gonna slam anything thats put in front of you.  Taste is secondary to thirst quenching.  So shut up and slam some Nattys!

Tap @ brewery.  I think they were trying for a Sierra Nevada-esque ale but failed.  Still, not too bad.  Aroma had a decent piney, honey scent.  Color was a wheat penny copper.  Lacing held out throughout the session.  I was expecting more, but still not a bad brew overall,  In fact, of the three brews I tried at this sitting, this was the best of the bunch.

Great coffeesque aroma and appearance.  Head was a little understated, but not bad.  Palate was suprisingly smooth, which I was not crazy about.  When drinking what is essentially an imperial stout, Id rather prefer a little more bite in the palate.  Taste is of fine roasted coffee and burnt grounds, which is good.  Overall, a pretty strudy beer for anyone who enjoys stouts.

22 oz bottle.  High, fluffy head and nice tan/copper color make for a nice presentation before even taking a sip.  But upon first sip, the enormous hoppy, sweet flavor immediately takes hold.  Add this with 9.9% ABV and you have the "perfect storm" of high hoppiness, high alcohol, and high times, baby!
beer_name: Avery The Maharaja Imperial India Pale Ale

review_blob: Only positive thing I can write about this horrid beer was its aroma - much like genuine root beer.  But you know - when I want something that tastes like root beer, Ill get a root beer.  A regular root beer is much tastier.  I hazard to even call this beer.  Its more like a bad root beer with some alcohol thrown in.

On draft @ MRBC in Savannah.  Nice color head, good body.  DeScription says this beer is supplemented w/ oats, which sort of takes away the whole point of an IPA.  As such, I kept asking myself "where are the hops"? I also noticed very little maltiness, so who knows where all those oats were.  Alcohol content was certainly noticed.  Overall, a decent beer but not one a raging hophead will love.

Draft @ Summits Wayside Tavern in Sandy Springs.  Though the barkeep highly recommended this "very special" brew, I was not overly impressed, though I admit I am not a big fan of BIG MALT, and this beer is certainly that - MALTY.  Ive had other genuine Belgium abbey strains of this variety and they seemed infinitely more complex and favlorful than this one.  Overall, a decent brew but not one that I would highly recommend.

Although not my favorite style, this one did nothing for me.  Appearance was only slightly darker than an American lager.  Head was initially significant, but fizzled away quickly.  Taste was of stale malt with a definite alcohol precense (bottle stated 6.3% abv). Bought a sampler twelve-pack of JWD to try it out and other than the really attractive price, I was not impressed with any of its offerings.  As they say, you get what you pay for.  This might be a good beer to have around when you have undesireable house guests over and want to "impress" them with something different, while you save the good stuff for you and your close friends.  You wont mind giving this beer away in droves because its cheap enough to do so.

Bottled.  Poured a nice, coppery color with lots of yeast "floaties".  Aroma was somewhat subdued, but taste more than made up for it.  Hoppy character was crsip and assertive, but not too much so.  I was more than pleasantly surprised by this one.  Pick a sixer up and youll be, too.

A spectacular IPA!  Good floral smell, nice hoppy bite.  Only drawback I give it is on appearance, as it is does not have the characteristic tawny, copper color of most IPAs.  Color is more pale.  No yeast "floaties" either.  I like floaties.  But the taste more than makes up for its uninspiring appearance.

On tap at Macons only brewery.  Nice jet black color and foamy, khaki head.  Smoky, charcoaly flavor was brief, but definitely there.  No bite here, though - silky smooth, almost like a Gunniess.  I would guess that alcohol content is quite low (< 5%).  Overall, not a bad beer from a joint where the home brews run the gauntlent from decent to dispicable.

One of my favorite IPAs of all time.  Excellent hazy orange color with lovely bits of sedement swirling about.  Has a definitive hoppy bite that grabs you by the balls and forces you to take notice.  As the bottle suggests, this one aint for beginners.  But if youre a well-traveled hop head, this beers for you.

This is a damn good beer!  Bought bottle in NJ (not available in GA - at least that I can find).  Nice classic IPA orange/copper color, fluffy egg-white head, and zingy hop flavor, but not one that hits you over the head - more subtle.   Definitely a grapefruitesque note in the palate.  Try this beer!

Bottled.  A heavily rated beer that does not dissappoint. Coppery color, fluffy head, grassy/hoppy bite - everything an IPA quaffin mofo would want.  That being said, theres another regional PA brewer that I think makes an even BETTER IPA: Lancasters Hop Hog IPA.  In my opinion, a notch above VHD.

Bottled.  A solid IPA from a great and (I hope) up and coming regional brewery.  Nice copper color, good fluffy head, decent Brussels lace, and (most importantly) a wicked hop bite that any hop-head will appreciate.  It was defintely worth "smuggling" a six pack of this down to GA from a recent trip up to NJ.  Try this beer!

Bought bottled near Andrews, NC.  Did not have the deep copper/orange color of most IPAs.  Fluffy head and decent Brussels lace, though.  Taste was somewhat hoppy, though couldve been more pronounced.  Overall, not a bad IPA.

Had this on tap at BBCs brewpub @ CVG.  Nice orange-copper color, nice crisp taste.  Hoppiness couldve been a little stronger but I guess they saved that for their IPA, which unfortunately was not available.

One of the most drab wheats Ive ever had.  No clove, no banana, no spice at all.  Not even a hint of lemon for chrissakes!  Head was virtually non-existent.  This beer might suffice on a hot golf course or fishing boat, but if Im sitting down at a bar I want to TASTE my beer.  I tasted very little in this one.

If I wouldve taken a blind taste test of this beer I would never have guessed that I was drinking an IPA.  Being an IPA-quaffin hop head, this was truly a disappointment for me... and Im from Macon.  Okay, for those bent on hearing the specifics here goes: color had a decent (though not rich) tawny, coppery hue.  Head was almost non-existent, but that couldve been from the bartenders piss-poor pour as Im sure most of his customers prefer their beer cold and decapitated.  Taste was the biggest buzz kill of all: very little hoppiness, lots of sloppiness.  An IPA with virtually no hop bite?  Need I say more?

A superb IPA!  Thick head, deep copper coler, nice brussels lace, and (best of all) a wicked, in-your-face, bite o hops dryness.  Back all this up with a firm 6.8% abv punch, and youve got a solid IPA here.  Swamp Fox reminds me a lot of another great GA-bred IPA: Sweetwater IPA.  Unfortunately, SF is only available on draft.  If youre ever in Savannah TRY THIS BEER!

Rich, ebony color.  Nice aroma.  Not much of a head though.  However, the smooth, roasted, nutty flavor make up for it.  Very smooth and drinkable for a brown ale.  This is the best of the lot @ Macons only brewery.
beer_name: Texas Cattle Honey Nut Brown Ale
